<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1437,529,1060]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,530,556]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Remarks:</emphasis>
The Madagascan race of the Eurasian Moorhen 
<taxonomicName authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[812,1235,529,556]" class="Aves" family="Rallidae" genus="Gallinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gruiformes" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chloropus">
<emphasis box="[812,1037,530,556]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Gallinula chloropus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." box="[1052,1227,529,556]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref49504" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1758) Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. 10 th Ed., vol. 1. Laurentii Salvii, Holmiae (Stockholm), 823 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 542" type="book" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is found throughout 
<collectingCountry box="[195,330,566,592]" name="Madagascar" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
and on the 
<collectingCountry box="[466,648,566,592]" name="Comoros" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Comoro Islands</collectingCountry>
, and is also a resident breeder on 
<collectingCountry box="[1034,1143,566,592]" name="Mauritius" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1200,1295,566,592]" name="Réunion" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Réunion</collectingCountry>
(A. 
<bibRefCitation author="Newton, A." pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="18 - 19" refId="ref51878" refString="Newton, A. (1861 a) Description of a new species of water-hen (Gallinula) from the island of Mauritius. Proceedings of the Scientific Meetings of the Zoological Society, 1, 18 - 19." type="journal article" year="1861">Newton 1861a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cheke, A. S. &amp; Hume, J. P." box="[235,478,602,628]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref43343" refString="Cheke, A. S. &amp; Hume, J. P. (2008) Lost Land of the Dodo: an Ecological History of Mauritius, Reunion &amp; Rodrigues. T. &amp; A. D. Poyser, London, 464 pp. [reprinted 2011]" type="book" year="2008">Cheke &amp; Hume 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Safford, R. J. &amp; Hawkins, A. F. A." box="[490,778,602,628]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref54791" refString="Safford, R. J. &amp; Hawkins, A. F. A. (2013) The birds of Africa. Volume VIII. The Malagasy Region. Christopher Helm, London, 1024 pp." type="book" year="2013">Safford &amp; Hawkins 2013</bibRefCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus box="[847,945,602,628]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[984,1184,602,628]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
G. c. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Newton" authorityYear="1861" box="[1045,1184,602,628]" class="Aves" family="Rallidae" genus="Gallinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gruiformes" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrrhorrhoa">pyrrhorrhoa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was collected in 1861 on 
<collectingCountry box="[189,301,638,664]" name="Mauritius" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
, when Alfred Newton received the skin from his brother, Edward (A. 
<bibRefCitation author="Newton, A." box="[1121,1291,638,664]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="18 - 19" refId="ref51878" refString="Newton, A. (1861 a) Description of a new species of water-hen (Gallinula) from the island of Mauritius. Proceedings of the Scientific Meetings of the Zoological Society, 1, 18 - 19." type="journal article" year="1861">Newton 1861a</bibRefCitation>
, b). Another specimen had been previously been collected in 1831 (
<bibRefCitation author="Desjardins, J." box="[765,953,674,700]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="45" refId="ref44211" refString="Desjardins, J. (1831) Abstract of the Proceedings of the &quot; Societe d'Histoire Naturelle de l'Isle Maurice, &quot; to the 24 th of August 1830. Proceedings of the Committee of the Science and Correspondence of the Zoological Society of London, 1, 45." type="journal article" year="1831">Desjardins 1831</bibRefCitation>
), at the same time that the eggs were probably recorded (
<bibRefCitation author="Cari, P." box="[321,439,710,736]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="121 - 128" refId="ref42849" refString="Cari, P. (1904) Observations sur quelques oiseaux de l'Ile Maurice. Ornis, 12, 121 - 128." type="journal article" year="1904">Cari 1904</bibRefCitation>
). Cossigny (Charpentier de 
<bibRefCitation author="Cossigny, J. F." box="[756,925,710,736]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 608" refId="ref42984" refString="Charpentier [de] Cossigny, J. F. (1799) Voyage a Canton, capitale de la province de ce nom, a la Chine: par Goree, le Cap de Bonne esperance et les iles de France et de la Reunion. Andre, Paris, i-viii + 1 - 608." type="book chapter" year="1799">Cossigny 1799</bibRefCitation>
) first observed them on 
<collectingCountry box="[1204,1313,710,736]" name="Mauritius" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
during the 1790s, and it appears that they were by then well established (
<bibRefCitation author="Cheke, A. S. &amp; Hume, J. P." box="[846,1092,746,772]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref43343" refString="Cheke, A. S. &amp; Hume, J. P. (2008) Lost Land of the Dodo: an Ecological History of Mauritius, Reunion &amp; Rodrigues. T. &amp; A. D. Poyser, London, 464 pp. [reprinted 2011]" type="book" year="2008">Cheke &amp; Hume 2008</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Michel, C." box="[1111,1272,746,772]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref50558" refString="Michel, C. (1992) Birds of Mauritius. 3 rd Edition. Editions de l'Ocean Indien, Stanley, Rose Hill, Mauritius, 46 pp." type="book" year="1992">Michel (1992)</bibRefCitation>
thought that it had been introduced by the French, but provides no evidence to support this claim and it appears unlikely. It was also first observed on 
<collectingCountry box="[395,490,818,844]" name="Réunion" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Réunion</collectingCountry>
in 1831 and was also considered common there at that time (
<bibRefCitation author="Sganzin" box="[1164,1322,818,844]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 49" refId="ref55649" refString="Sganzin, 1840) Notes sur les mammiferes et sur l'ornithologie de l'ile de Madagascar. Memoires de le Societe du Museum d'Histoire Naturelle de Strasbourg, 3 (1), 1 - 49." type="journal article" year="1840">Sganzin 1840</bibRefCitation>
). The lack of records from the 17th century, plus its absence from the fossil-rich Mare aux Songes deposits, suggests that 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
G. c. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Newton" authorityYear="1861" box="[179,318,890,916]" class="Aves" family="Rallidae" genus="Gallinula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gruiformes" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyrrhorrhoa">pyrrhorrhoa</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is a recent colonist that may well have populated the niche of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1867" box="[1032,1209,890,916]" class="Aves" family="Rallidae" genus="Fulica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gruiformes" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="newtonii">
<emphasis box="[1032,1209,890,916]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fulica newtonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
after it had become extinct (
<bibRefCitation author="Cheke, A. S. &amp; Hume, J. P." box="[242,485,926,952]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref43343" refString="Cheke, A. S. &amp; Hume, J. P. (2008) Lost Land of the Dodo: an Ecological History of Mauritius, Reunion &amp; Rodrigues. T. &amp; A. D. Poyser, London, 464 pp. [reprinted 2011]" type="book" year="2008">Cheke &amp; Hume 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hume, J. P." box="[497,634,926,952]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="195 - 237" refId="ref48084" refString="Hume, J. P. (2013) A synopsis of the pre-human avifauna of the Mascarene Islands. In: Gohlich, U. B. &amp; Kroh, A. (Eds.), Proceedings of the 8 th International Meeting of the Society of Avian Paleontology and Evolution. Naturhistorisches Museum, Wien, pp. 195 - 237." type="book chapter" year="2013">Hume 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1437,529,1060]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
The Madagascan Moorhen occurs in most remaining wetland areas of 
<collectingCountry box="[997,1106,962,988]" name="Mauritius" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mauritius</collectingCountry>
today, especially in the north where it is abundant (pers. obs) (
<figureCitation box="[521,605,998,1024]" captionStart="FIGURE 38" captionStartId="60.[151,250,1937,1962]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1081,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@60.[151,1436,1081,1916]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURE 38. The last surviving Mascarene rail, Madagascan Moorhen Gallinula chloropus pyrrhorrhoa (centre on rock), at the coastal Anse la Raie wetlands on the northern tip of Mauritius. This was once the habitat of Fulica newtonii. Photograph by the author." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3335563/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
), and is well established on the Étang St. Paul and other wetland areas up to an altitude of 
<quantity box="[335,427,1034,1060]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="m" value="1000.0">1,000 m</quantity>
on 
<collectingCountry box="[469,564,1034,1060]" name="Réunion" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Réunion</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Milon, P." box="[578,714,1033,1060]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="129 - 178" refId="ref50626" refString="Milon, P. (1951) Notes sur l'avifaune actuelle de I'ile de la Reunion. Terre Vie, 98, 129 - 178." type="journal article" year="1951">Milon 1951</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Safford, R. J. &amp; Hawkins, A. F. A." box="[726,1013,1034,1060]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref54791" refString="Safford, R. J. &amp; Hawkins, A. F. A. (2013) The birds of Africa. Volume VIII. The Malagasy Region. Christopher Helm, London, 1024 pp." type="book" year="2013">Safford &amp; Hawkins 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
